Repo Reader Agent — Detailed Design
Companion document to the TestForge architecture. This document is the full specification for the Repo Reader agent: the first non-orchestrator agent in the flow. It is responsible for acquiring the target repository, analysing its entire codebase, and producing two outputs that every downstream agent depends on.

1. Purpose & Position in the Flow
The Repo Reader is the discovery layer of TestForge. Everything downstream — the Scraper, the BE Test Writer, the FE Test Writer, and the Reviewer — operates on the artefacts this agent produces. If the Repo Reader's output is wrong, incomplete, or unstructured, the rest of the system degrades quickly.

CONFIG ──▶ ORC ──▶ ┌─────────────────┐ ──▶ SCRAPER ──▶ WRITERS ──▶ REVIEWER
                   │   REPO READER    │
                   │  (this agent)    │
                   └─────────────────┘
                            │
                            ├──▶ codebase-overview.txt   (human-readable narrative)
                            └──▶ context-document.md     (structured, schema-driven)
Contract with the rest of the system
Concern	Commitment
Inputs accepted	Local path OR git URL (public) OR git URL + PAT (private)
Stack assumption	None. Generic discovery across any language/framework
Outputs produced	codebase-overview.txt + context-document.md (both required)
Side effects on target repo	Read-only. Never writes, modifies, or commits to the target
Failure mode	Fail fast with clear diagnostics; never produce a partial context doc and pretend it's complete
2. Inputs
The agent accepts three input shapes. The Orchestrator resolves which shape is in play and normalises before invoking the Repo Reader.

2.1 Input shape A — Local path (already cloned)
{
  "source_type": "local",
  "repo_path": "/absolute/path/to/repo"
}
Validation: path exists, is a directory, contains a .git folder (warn but proceed if not — could be an exported codebase).

2.2 Input shape B — Public git URL
{
  "source_type": "git_public",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/owner/repo.git",
  "branch": "main"
}
The Repo Reader clones into a temp directory: /tmp/testforge-repos/<sha256(url)>-<timestamp>/. Shallow clone (--depth 50) by default to save bandwidth while keeping enough history for any "what changed recently" heuristics.

2.3 Input shape C — Private git URL
{
  "source_type": "git_private",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/owner/repo.git",
  "branch": "main",
  "auth": {
    "method": "pat",
    "pat_source": "file" | "env" | "prompt",
    "pat_file_path": "./github-pat.txt",
    "pat_env_var": "TESTFORGE_GITHUB_PAT"
  }
}
PAT resolution order (the agent tries each in turn, first success wins):

Explicit file — if pat_source: "file" and pat_file_path is set, read trimmed contents of that file. File must have permissions 0600 or stricter on POSIX; if not, the agent refuses and tells the user to chmod 600 it.
Environment variable — if pat_source: "env" or as a fallback, read from pat_env_var (default TESTFORGE_GITHUB_PAT).
Interactive prompt — if pat_source: "prompt" or all above fail, ask the user via the CLI (getpass, never echoed). Only used in interactive runs.
The PAT is held in memory for the duration of the clone, then explicitly cleared (del pat; gc.collect()). It is never logged, never written to disk by TestForge, and never included in any output artefact.

2.4 Auto-detection (when source_type is omitted)
If the orchestrator passes only a string: - Starts with http://, https://, or git@ → treat as git URL → try unauthenticated clone first → if it fails with auth error, escalate to private flow - Otherwise → treat as local path

3. Outputs
The Repo Reader produces two artefacts, both required, written to the TestForge run's working directory.

3.1 codebase-overview.txt — Free-form narrative
A plain-text, human-readable explanation of the repository. Written in prose. No headings required, no schema. Audience: a tester or engineer who has never seen this codebase and needs to understand it well enough to write tests.

Target length: 800–2000 words depending on repo size. Should answer questions like:

What does this application do, in plain language?
Who are the users and what do they do with it?
What is the architecture in broad strokes (monolith, microservices, frontend/backend split)?
Where are the important parts of the code? What lives where?
What's the auth and permissions model?
What's unusual or worth knowing before writing tests?
What are the risky areas — places where bugs are likely?
This file exists specifically because target repos often have no README or stale docs. It becomes the "if you read one thing before starting, read this" document.

3.2 context-document.md — Structured schema
A markdown document with a strict, schema-driven structure so downstream agents (Scraper, Writers) can reliably extract sections by heading. Every section in the schema below MUST appear, even if empty (with an explicit "Not applicable" or "Not detected" note).

Schema for context-document.md
---
repo_name: <string>
repo_source: <local | git_public | git_private>
analysed_at: <ISO 8601 timestamp>
analyser_version: <semver>
commit_sha: <git SHA if available>
---

