- **Framework:** <pytest | jest | etc.>
- **Coverage estimate:** <if discoverable from coverage reports>
- **Test file count:** <integer>
- **Patterns observed:** <e.g., uses factory-boy fixtures, beforeEach hooks>
- **Gaps observed:** <e.g., no integration tests, no role-permission tests>

## 10. Risk & Test Priority Hints
> Subjective annotations from the analyser. Things the Test Writers should prioritise.

- **High-risk areas:** <e.g., payment processing in src/billing/, recently modified per git log>
- **Permission boundaries:** <e.g., admin endpoints accessible from user routes — needs negative tests>
- **Untested critical paths:** <e.g., user registration has no existing tests>
- **Known fragile areas:** <e.g., TODO/FIXME comments in src/sync/>

## 11. Environment & Configuration
- **Required env vars:** <as extracted from .env.example, config files>
- **Default ports:** <backend port, frontend dev port>
- **External services (mocked vs real):** <e.g., Stripe in test mode, SendGrid mocked>

## 12. Open Questions / Confidence Notes
> Where the analyser was uncertain. Honest signalling so downstream agents don't over-trust.

- The role `editor` is referenced in 2 files but never defined — possibly dead code or external integration
- Several endpoints lack explicit auth decorators; reading the middleware suggests they're protected globally, but the Scraper should confirm
- The frontend appears to have feature flags (`useFeatureFlag(...)`) — coverage of disabled paths may not be possible without flag overrides
Why a strict schema
Downstream agents read this file via section headings. If the schema drifts (Scraper expects ## 4. Routes & Endpoints but the Repo Reader emits ## Endpoints), the pipeline silently degrades. The schema is enforced by a post-generation validator (see section 6.4).

4. Analysis Strategy — Hybrid Approach
A real codebase has thousands of files. We cannot feed all of them to the LLM. The Repo Reader runs a hybrid pipeline: heuristics narrow the scope to high-signal files, then LLM passes synthesise the outputs.

4.1 Pass 0 — Acquisition
Resolve input shape (local / public / private).
If git-based: clone to temp dir with shallow depth.
Verify accessibility, record commit_sha.
4.2 Pass 1 — Heuristic Scan (no LLM, pure code)
Walk the file tree once. Build a structured inventory in memory. No LLM calls in this pass.

Detect tech stack via marker files:

Marker file	Implies
package.json	Node.js project — parse for framework deps (express, next, react, etc.)
pyproject.toml / requirements.txt / setup.py	Python — parse for fastapi, django, flask, sqlalchemy
Gemfile	Ruby — parse for rails, sinatra
go.mod	Go — parse for gin, echo, fiber
pom.xml / build.gradle	Java/Kotlin — parse for spring
Cargo.toml	Rust
composer.json	PHP — parse for laravel, symfony
.csproj	.NET
Dockerfile / docker-compose.yml	Containerised — parse for service hints
prisma/schema.prisma	Prisma ORM
alembic.ini / migrations/	DB migrations present
.env.example / .env.sample	Env var inventory
Classify every file into a tier:

Tier	Definition	Treatment
Tier 1 — Critical	Routes, controllers, models, auth middleware, config, schema	Read in full, send to LLM
Tier 2 — Supporting	Services, utilities referenced by Tier 1, fixtures, existing tests	Read in full if budget allows; otherwise summary only
Tier 3 — Boilerplate	Generated files, lockfiles, build outputs, node_modules, vendor/, .git/	Skip entirely
Tier 4 — Documentation	README, docs/, CHANGELOG	Read in full — high signal, low cost
Tier 1 detection heuristics (generic across stacks):

Filenames or paths containing: routes, controllers, handlers, endpoints, views, api, models, schemas, entities, auth, middleware, permissions, policies
Files containing route-definition patterns: @app.get, @router., app.get(, router.post(, @RequestMapping, resources :, Route::, func .* (w http.ResponseWriter, etc.
Files importing ORM base classes
Config files: *.config.*, settings.py, config/*.{js,ts,yml}
Skip patterns (always):

node_modules/  vendor/  .git/  dist/  build/  target/  __pycache__/
*.min.js  *.min.css  *.lock  *.lockb  .DS_Store  coverage/
.next/  .nuxt/  .venv/  venv/  *.pyc
Output of Pass 1: an in-memory FileInventory object with tier-classified file paths, detected stack markers, and a rough size estimate of what the LLM will need to ingest.

4.3 Pass 2 — Targeted LLM Reads
For each Tier 1 file, send the file contents to the LLM (Claude Sonnet 4) with a focused prompt: "Extract from this file: routes defined, models defined, auth checks, role references. Respond as JSON with this schema."

Batched in groups of ~5-10 files per LLM call to stay under context limits and reduce cost. Each batch produces a partial structured result that gets merged into a running aggregate.

If total Tier 1 content exceeds a configurable budget (default ~200K tokens of source): demote lowest-priority Tier 1 files to "summary only" mode — LLM gets just the file path, first 50 lines, and last 20 lines, with a note that the file was truncated.

4.4 Pass 3 — Synthesis
Two LLM calls produce the two outputs:

context-document.md — LLM is given the aggregated structured data from Pass 2 plus the schema template, and asked to fill it in. Strict instruction: every heading present, no invented data, mark unknowns as "Not detected."

codebase-overview.txt — LLM is given the same aggregate plus the context document it just produced, and asked to write a 800-2000 word narrative for a tester encountering the codebase cold.

These two synthesis calls use Claude Sonnet 4 (high quality required) and run sequentially — overview after context, so overview can reference the structured findings without contradicting them.

4.5 Pass 4 — Validation
A pure-code validator (no LLM) checks:

context-document.md contains all 12 required top-level sections in order
Frontmatter is well-formed YAML
Tables in sections 4, 5, 6 have the required columns
No section is completely empty (must have at least "Not detected" or "Not applicable")
If validation fails: one retry of Pass 3 with the validator's complaints fed back. If it fails again: emit what we have, log the gaps, raise a warning to the Orchestrator. Do not silently ship malformed output.

5. Tools Used by the Agent
Tool	Purpose	When used
file_read_tool	Read individual files	Pass 1 (markers), Pass 2 (Tier 1 contents)
directory_list_tool	Walk the file tree	Pass 1
git_clone_tool	Clone public/private repos	Pass 0 (when input is a URL)
git_metadata_tool	Get commit SHA, branch, last-modified-per-file	Pass 0, Pass 1 (risk hints)
file_write_tool	Write the two output artefacts	Pass 3 / Pass 4
schema_validator_tool	Validate context-document.md against the schema	Pass 4
git_clone_tool and git_metadata_tool are new and need to be implemented under src/testforge/tools/git_tools.py.

6. CrewAI Agent Definition
6.1 agents.yaml
repo_reader:
  role: "Codebase Analyst"
  goal: >
    Produce two artefacts for the target repository:
    (1) a structured context-document.md following the TestForge schema, and
    (2) a free-form codebase-overview.txt narrative.
    The outputs must be accurate, complete on all required sections, and honest
    about uncertainty.
  backstory: >
    You are a senior software engineer who joins new projects regularly and
    becomes productive on day two. You read code methodically, recognise
    framework conventions across many languages, and write clear documentation
    for the next person who will work on the codebase. You distinguish what
    you know from what you're guessing, and you say so.
  tools:
    - file_read_tool
    - directory_list_tool
    - git_clone_tool
    - git_metadata_tool
    - file_write_tool
    - schema_validator_tool
  llm: claude-sonnet-4
  max_iter: 5
  memory: true
  verbose: true
6.2 tasks.yaml
acquire_repository:
  description: >
    Resolve the repository input and make it available locally.
    Input shape: {source_type, repo_path | repo_url, branch?, auth?}
    If source_type is git_public or git_private, clone to a temp directory.
    For git_private, resolve PAT via the documented resolution order.
    Record the commit SHA. Validate the working tree exists and is readable.
  expected_output: >
    A LocalRepoHandle with {local_path, commit_sha, branch, source_metadata}.
  agent: repo_reader

scan_filesystem:
  description: >
    Walk the repository tree (excluding skip-patterns) and classify every file
    into Tiers 1-4. Detect tech stack from marker files. Produce a FileInventory.
  expected_output: >
    A FileInventory object listing files per tier, detected stack markers,
    and an estimate of total Tier 1 token size.
  agent: repo_reader
  context:
    - acquire_repository

extract_structured_data:
  description: >
    For each Tier 1 file (and Tier 2 files within budget), extract routes,
    models, auth references, role references, and config values. Aggregate
    findings into a structured intermediate representation.
  expected_output: >
    An aggregated dictionary keyed by category (routes, models, roles, etc.)
    with source-file references for traceability.
  agent: repo_reader
  context:
    - scan_filesystem

synthesise_context_document:
  description: >
    Given the structured findings, produce context-document.md following the
    TestForge schema exactly. Every required section must appear. Unknown
    values are marked "Not detected." Do not invent data.
  expected_output: >
    A markdown string conforming to the context-document schema.
  agent: repo_reader
  context:
    - extract_structured_data

synthesise_overview_narrative:
  description: >
    Given the structured findings and the context document, write a 800-2000
    word free-form narrative explaining the codebase to a tester who has never
    seen it. Plain prose, no markdown headings required.
  expected_output: >
    A plain-text narrative.
  agent: repo_reader
  context:
    - synthesise_context_document

validate_and_write:
  description: >
    Run the schema validator over the context document. If it fails, retry the
    synthesis once with the validator's feedback. Write both artefacts to the
    output directory. Update shared state with file paths.
  expected_output: >
    Paths to context-document.md and codebase-overview.txt, plus a
    validation report.
  agent: repo_reader
  context:
    - synthesise_context_document
    - synthesise_overview_narrative
6.3 Updates to TestForgeState
Two new fields are needed on the shared state to expose the Repo Reader's outputs to downstream agents:

# Add to TestForgeState:
context_document_path: str = ""      # Path to context-document.md
codebase_overview_path: str = ""     # Path to codebase-overview.txt
repo_local_path: str = ""            # Resolved local path (for downstream file reads)
repo_commit_sha: str = ""            # For reproducibility / debugging
analyser_confidence: dict = field(default_factory=dict)
    # {section_name: "high"|"medium"|"low"} — signals to downstream agents
The existing context_document: str field stays as the in-memory copy for agents that don't want to re-read from disk.

6.4 Schema Validator
A small pure-Python validator at src/testforge/tools/schema_validator.py:

REQUIRED_SECTIONS = [
    "## 1. Tech Stack",
    "## 2. Repository Structure",
    "## 3. Entry Points",
    "## 4. Routes & Endpoints",
    "## 5. Data Models",
    "## 6. Authentication & Authorization",
    "## 7. Business Domain Glossary",
    "## 8. Module Dependency Map",
    "## 9. Existing Test Suite",
    "## 10. Risk & Test Priority Hints",
    "## 11. Environment & Configuration",
    "## 12. Open Questions / Confidence Notes",
]

def validate_context_document(md: str) -> ValidationResult:
    # 1. Frontmatter parses as YAML and has required keys
    # 2. Each required section heading appears, in order
    # 3. No section is empty (>= 1 line of content)
    # 4. Tables in §4, §5, §6 have the right column headers
    ...
7. Failure Modes & Handling
Scenario	Handling
Local path doesn't exist	Fail immediately, clear error to Orchestrator
Git URL unreachable (network)	Retry 2x with backoff, then fail
Private repo, no PAT resolvable	Fail with instruction: "Provide PAT via file, env var, or interactive prompt"
PAT file has wrong permissions	Fail with instruction to chmod 600
PAT is invalid (401/403 from git)	Fail with explicit "auth failed" — do not retry, do not log the PAT
Repo is empty or has no source files	Produce minimal outputs marked "Empty repository — no analysis possible"
Repo is gigantic (>100K files)	Apply aggressive Tier 3 skipping, warn in confidence notes
Tier 1 content exceeds LLM budget	Truncate per Pass 2 strategy, note truncation in §12
LLM returns malformed structured data	Retry once with stricter prompt; if still bad, drop the bad file and continue
Schema validator fails after retry	Emit what we have, log all violations, flag downstream agents to treat output with caution
Unsupported language / unknown stack	Still produce outputs; mark stack as "Unrecognised — generic analysis only"
The agent's commitment is: always produce both output files, even degraded. Empty schema sections are explicit ("Not detected"), never silently missing. Downstream agents can then make informed decisions about how much to trust each section.

8. Performance & Cost Considerations
Lever	Default	Tuneable
Shallow clone depth	50 commits	--clone-depth CLI flag
Pass 2 batch size	8 files per LLM call	Config
Pass 2 total budget	200K tokens of source	--max-source-tokens
Tier 2 inclusion	On if budget allows	--skip-tier-2 to force off
Synthesis model	Claude Sonnet 4	--repo-reader-model
Cost ceiling for a typical mid-sized repo (~500 source files, ~50 Tier 1): - Pass 2: ~10 batched LLM calls @ ~15K tokens each ≈ 150K input tokens - Pass 3: 2 synthesis calls @ ~30K input + ~5K output each - Estimated total: ~250K input / ~12K output Sonnet tokens per run

This is the most expensive single agent in TestForge. Tier classification exists specifically to keep this bounded.

9. Security Considerations
Concern	Mitigation
PAT exposure in logs	Explicit redaction in logger; PAT never passed as CLI arg, only via file/env/prompt
PAT exposure in output artefacts	Outputs are generated from analysis results, never from raw config; PAT is structurally not in the data flow after clone
Cloned repo persistence	Temp dirs cleaned up on success; on failure, path is logged so user can inspect, but a --cleanup-on-failure flag forces deletion
Reading sensitive files (.env with real secrets)	Real .env files are read for variable names only; values are redacted in any output. .env.example is read normally
Malicious repo content	We only read files, never execute. No eval, no exec, no running of the target's scripts
Symlink escape	File walker resolves symlinks and rejects any that point outside the repo root
Path traversal in inputs	All input paths are resolved to absolute, canonical form before use
10. Definition of Done
The Repo Reader's task is complete when all of the following hold:

context-document.md exists at the configured output path
codebase-overview.txt exists at the configured output path
Schema validator returns PASS on the context document (or, after one retry, PASS_WITH_WARNINGS logged)
Shared state has context_document_path, codebase_overview_path, repo_local_path, and repo_commit_sha populated
Any temp clones are either retained at a known path or cleaned, depending on config
PAT (if used) has been cleared from memory
The Orchestrator has been signalled that the next agent (Scraper) can begin
11. Open Questions for the Team
Things flagged for the wider TestForge team to confirm before implementation:

Clone location — Is /tmp/testforge-repos/ acceptable, or do we want a configurable working dir under the TestForge output directory so everything is co-located per run?
Branch selection — Default to repo's default branch (detected via git remote show origin), or require explicit --branch?
Submodules — Recurse into git submodules, or treat them as Tier 3 and skip? Default proposal: skip, note in §12.
Monorepo handling — If the repo is a monorepo with multiple apps (e.g., apps/web, apps/api), do we analyse the whole thing or accept a --subpath to narrow scope? Default proposal: analyse whole; add --subpath later if needed.
Existing-doc precedence — If the repo has a high-quality README or docs/ folder, do we lean on it (faster, less LLM cost) or ignore it and analyse from source (more reliable)? Default proposal: read it as Tier 4 input, but don't trust it as ground truth — verify against source where they conflict.
Caching across runs — If the same commit_sha is analysed twice, can we reuse the previous outputs? Useful for iteration during the competition demo. Default proposal: opt-in via --use-cache.
12. Handoff to Downstream Agents
The Repo Reader's outputs are consumed as follows:

Downstream agent	Consumes	How
Scraper	context-document.md §4 (Route inventory) + §6 (Auth) + raw repo access	Uses inventory as a starting checklist; expands each entry into full API spec
BE Test Writer	Full context-document.md + codebase-overview.txt (for context)	Schema sections drive structured test planning; narrative gives domain understanding
FE Test Writer	Full context-document.md + codebase-overview.txt + app URL	§4.2 (frontend routes) and §6 (roles) are the primary inputs
Reviewer	codebase-overview.txt for context when diagnosing failures	Used only when the reviewer needs to judge whether a failure is a test bug or an app bug
This handoff is the reason §12 (Open Questions / Confidence Notes) of the context document matters: it tells downstream agents which sections to trust fully and which to verify before acting on.